<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-064-318  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 064 318.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Jan 15 1990 n253 p77(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>And now from Levi's: designer databases; jeans giant trims downthrough staff cuts and leveraged buyout. (Levi Strauss andamp; Co.)andO;(company profile)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Todd, Daniel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Levi Strauss andamp; Co was forced to cut its workforce by a third inthe 1980s and began a $1.6 billion leveraged buyout to take thecompany private, so to revitalize its operations it turned toinformation technology.andP;  The company hopes the integration ofretailer cash register, factory floor and back-room systems anddatabases will make its employees more responsive to customers andto the fast pace of change in the clothing industry.andP;  Levi Straussplans to connect with trading partners, suppliers, manufacturersand retailers to smooth the flow of information between each.andP;  The'Quick Response' initiative of Levi Strauss and other apparelmakers and sellers combines universal product codes (UPCs), POSscanners and terminals, and electronic data interchange.andP;  TheLeviLink computer-integrated manufacturing system, Levi's AdvancedBusiness System and Real-time productivity CIM tool are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Levi Strauss and Co. (automation).andO;Topic:     ClothingGarment IndustryAutomationApplicationsCompany ProfileMISManagement of EDP.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>